Date: 0/0/1966
Source: English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author: TURNER
Vol / Page: 121
Edition:
Quote: A <i>snitch </i> is a grudge or dislike, probably related to the underworld term recorded by Vaux in 1812, <i>to snitch </i> `to betray', and probably unconnected with Australian and New Zealand <i>snitcher </i> `excellent'.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1943
Source: English as it is spoken in NZ
Author: BENNETT
Vol / Page: 90
Edition:
Quote: A person complaining of another's ill-will might also say, `He's got a proper snitch on me' - obviously a variant of `to snitch upon' (to inform against)
